        "text": "ἐκτινάσσοντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Dean Farrar refers to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Pal. Expln. Fund",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 1879, p, 77, for instances of the sudden excitability of Oriental crowds, and for similar illustrations see Hackett, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κονιορτὸν βαλλ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: best taken as another sign of the same rage and fury, a similar demonstration; this is preferable to the supposition that they threw dust into the air to signify that they would throw stones if they could. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εἰς τὸν ἀέρα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
